{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13999"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13999"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.02,0.05,0.64,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6633"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"82"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"13217"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl is brought to the Emergency Department after a sudden onset palpitations and shortness of breath. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears anxious with a heart rate of 240/min and blood pressure 100/60 mmHg. An ECG is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the underlying mechanism of this arrhythmia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased automaticity of the sinus node","Conduction block in the bundle of His","Ectopic focus in the right ventricle","Re-entry circuit involving an accessory pathway","Triggered activity in the Purkinje fibers"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and ECG findings in this case are consistent with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) in a child. The most common mechanism of SVT in children is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ere-entry circuit involving an accessory pathway\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the correct answer. This is typically seen in Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome, where an extra electrical connection exists between the atria and ventricles, allowing for a circular electrical pathway that can sustain a rapid heart rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased automaticity of the sinus node\u003C/strong\u003E can cause sinus tachycardia, but this typically has a more gradual onset and rarely exceeds 200/min in children. Additionally, P waves would be visible on the ECG in sinus tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriggered activity in the Purkinje fibers\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with ventricular arrhythmias rather than SVT. The narrow QRS complexes in this case indicate a supraventricular origin of the tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic focus in the right ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E would result in a wide complex tachycardia, which is not consistent with the narrow complex tachycardia described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduction block in the bundle of His\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes bradyarrhythmias rather than tachyarrhythmias and would not explain the rapid heart rate seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while reentry involving an accessory pathway is the most common mechanism, AV nodal re-entry tachycardia (AVNRT) is also a frequent cause of SVT in children. Both mechanisms involve re-entry circuits, but AVNRT uses the AV node itself rather than an accessory pathway. The management of acute SVT in children typically involves vagal manoeuvers followed by adenosine administration if necessary. Long-term management may include medication or catheter ablation of the accessory pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) in children is most commonly due to an accessory pathway or AV nodal reentry.","The typical heart rate in paediatric SVT is 220-300/min.","Adenosine is the first-line treatment for acute SVT in children due to its rapid onset and short half-life."],"references":["UpToDate. Narrow QRS complex tachycardias: Clinical manifestations, diagnosis, and evaluation [Internet]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/narrow-qrs-complex-tachycardias-clinical-manifestations-diagnosis-and-evaluation?search=svt\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E70\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35237"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13999"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20891"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20891"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6r9XUEFn9a6ZRYrbg5Mk5DROOrrVH.jpg","thumbUrl